17. Difference between return and print
The core difference is that print displays information to the human user on the screen, 
while return hands a value back to the computer program so it can be saved and used in subsequent calculations.

def add_with_print(a, b):
    print(a + b)  # This only shows the text on your screen
# Running this will show "5" on the screen

result = add_with_print(2, 3) 
# Trying to use the variable will fail because nothing was saved
print(result)  # Output (None)

def add_with_return(a, b):
    return a + b  # This passes the data back to the script
# The number 5 is successfully saved into the variable
saved_total = add_with_return(2, 3) 
# Now the computer can use that data for further math
final_calculation = saved_total * 10
print(final_calculation)  # Output: 50

18. What are *args and **kwargs?
In Python, *args and **kwargs are special symbols used in function definitions to allow them to accept an arbitrary(multiple) number of inputs.
*args - allows a func to accept any number of position arguments - takes inp as tuples and rteurns value
*kwargs - allows a func to accept any number of keyword arguments - takes inp as keyword and returns out as dict

def add(*args):
    return sum(args)
print(add(10, 20, 30)) #60

def student(**kwargs):
    print(kwargs)
student(name="Nav", age=22)  #{'name': 'Nav', 'age': 22}

